The defendant Daniel Edward Kroening was found guilty of the following charge(s) in this case.

  • OWI (4th w/in 5 yrs), a class H felony, Wisconsin Statutes 346.63(1)(a).

Notice to employers: It may be a violation of state law to discriminate against a job applicant because of an arrest or conviction record. Generally speaking, an employer may refuse to hire an applicant on the basis of a conviction only if the circumstances of the conviction substantially relate to the particular job. For more information, see Wisconsin Statute 111.335 and the Department of Workforce Development's publication, Arrest and Conviction Records under the Law.

records.addlTxt:
Defendant Daniel Edward Kroening in court with attorney Victoria Mccandless.  Sara Nicole Volden Schroeder appeared for the State of Wisconsin.  Plea hearing proceeds.  Defendant was advised of constitutional rights and maximum penalties, and further advised that if not a United States citizen deportation is possible. Defendant sworn, examined as to plea, and entered a plea of guilty.  Court found defendant freely, voluntarily and intelligently waived all constitutional rights. Plea questionnaire waiver of rights and addendum to plea questionnaire received and filed. Parties stipulated to the criminal complaint as factual basis to sustain defendant's plea. Court found defendant guilty as charged in the Information and ordered a Judgment of Conviction be entered into the record.  The Court advised defendant that as a convicted felon not to possess any firearms.   Court further advised defendant of voting ineligibility.   

Sentencing proceeded.  Statements by the State, defense and defendant.  The Court imposed the following sentence:  The Court imposed 12 months at the House of Correction, with Huber for work; good time also allowed; 4 days credit.  Court did not object to transfer of sentence to the Ozaukee County Jail if that jail accepts him.  
 * Court ordered defendant to pay a $600.00 fine, plus costs, DNA surcharge and disbursements and other surcharges.  Court allowed defendant 18 months to pay (by 11/28/16).  Failure to pay amounts in full would result in a civil judgment entered against defendant.
 * Court ordered defendant to provide a DNA sample;
 * Court ordered defendant to complete a Driver Assessment and Safety Plan; Court Order for IDP Related Offense Driver Assessment and Driver Safety Plan, signed and filed; copy provided to defendant.
 * Court ordered a 2-year driver's license revocation and a 2-year ignition interlock.
